<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-831-413  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 831 413.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 8 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australian retailing: IBM's discounting fervour.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McNamara, Sean.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Marketing).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     AustraliaComputer industryMarketing StrategyDistribution ManagementDiscount.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AUSTRALIAN RETAILING: IBM'S DISCOUNTING FERVOUR SYDNEY, AUSTRALIA, 1990 MAY 3(NB) -- Despite statements that IBM is a &quot;one-price house,&quot; it appearsAustralian purchasers have been receiving huge discounts on list prices.andP;  Forlarger purchasers, IBM uses &quot;special bids&quot; or a &quot;volume procurement basis&quot;for determining discounts of around 10-20%, and even, say some sources, up to50%.andP;  List prices, however, are 25-35% higher than US list prices, even afterexchange rates, import duties, freight costs, insurance and other suchvariables are taken into account.andM;IBM has stated that these variations are affected by market cost structures,which take into account market size, import charges and distance frommanufacturing site.andP;  The manager of a large Queensland site with several IBMmainframes has observed that the situation has come to the point where &quot;everybid is a special bid.&quot; But this may now change after IBM's write-off ofUS$2.5B last year.andM;Discounts to this extent have reduced IBM's margins by 62-54% over the lastfour to five years, according to Bernie Armstrong, vice-president of theGartner Group.andM;(Sean McNamara/19900504)</TEXT></DOC>